Episode One: "Ways to make a bad first impression" - PBJ Sake: Spirits were high at the Sake tribe, as the energetic new castaways dominated in the first challenge. Jenna was able to do a lot of legwork for the more specific items, while Pickles and Kyran focused on art, and Zacharie and Winley on video tasks. However, everyone contributed to a variety of categories on the challenge, allowing them to keep up a quick pace. Sake were able to come together to complete more teamwork oriented tasks than any tribe, netting them the highest score in the challenge of 39 out of a possible 48 points! On the social side, Jenna and Pickles were able to connect early and quickly become each other’s most trusted, establishing a flow of information on their tribe that netted them both CPs. Zacharie was one of the quieter voices on the tribe and in the challenge, but their impeccable selfie game and charisma had them viewed positively by the tribe and got them a low visibility MORP rating. In contrast, after Winley had a very productive performance at the beginning of the challenge, people felt conversations stalling out in 1on1s which caused them to fall to the bottom of the trust rankings. That, combined with Winley feeling sick and being unavailable to contribute after the night of the challenge announcement got them a MORM rating. Kyran had a decent prescience in the challenge, but connected most to Zacharie who was around the least, and was immediately wary of Jenna who he perceived to be a strong threat. Overall, Kyran’s lack of connection to active players caused him to drop in the trust rankings and got him a MOR for the episode. Unagi: The Unagi tribe was a storm of social activity, especially for not having a tribal to go to! Right off the bat, Etay, PBJ, and Annie are chatting it up and quickly realize that they all want to work together. They form an alliance they call APEs, and begin talking there regularly. This earns PBJ and Annie CP ratings for the episode, as they were members of the key trio on Unagi as well as did great work on the challenge. Etay gets an OTT though, for being a bit too focused on the immediate social activity of the tribe. His constant emphasis on one-on-one message counts showed that he might read too much into certain details of the game. The other tribe members, Fones and Stephen were notably less present than the APEs trio. They contributed some to the challenge and some to the social game, but it was noted they were clearly less active than the others. This gets them both UTR ratings, since they kept up with the tribe but were not major contributors to the dynamics.
12:01 AM
Ebi: The Ebi tribe was a bit of a mixed bag in terms of player activity and sociability. Noah and Taco were fairly inactive at the start, leading Mana, Sky and Treb to come together as a trio, reinforced by their activity and performance in the challenge. While they ultimately were not able to pick up enough slack to avoid tribal, Treb created an alliance with Mana and Sky called Slay-Ebiday which would become crucial for the next few votes. Taco sensing that he may be in danger attempted to form an alliance with Treb and Sky, but it was ultimately unsuccessful. The Ebiday’s had to decide between Taco and Noah and although Taco was more active, the overall negative reception to his challenge performance coupled with the understanding that Noah was busy the first two days was enough to lean towards Taco. The vote would be a simple 4-1 with Taco being eliminated and Noah receiving the stray vote. Treb gets a CPP for his overall positive perception from the tribe, his challenge performance, strategic musings and for bringing together the Slay-Ebiday group. Mana and Sky both get P tones for their upbeat attitudes and reception from their tribemates. Taco gets an N tone for his slight attitude during the challenge which rubbed his tribemates the wrong way. Noah gets a UTR for being basically inactive for the first two days outside of a couple short messages. Hokkigai: The Hokkigai tribe got off to a much slower start out of the gate, seeing significantly less activity in comparison to the other tribes. Dylan became unable to participate in the game due to irl commitments, and was substituted for Aura. The more hands-off approach of Hokkigai was felt not only in the minimal communication among the tribe, but in the scavenger hunt bingo challenge as well. The first night of the challenge saw Dicy be the only member to submit any items, and not a single bingo was scored until the next day. After a night of relaxing, Slaytan went into overdrive and ended up contributing the most items of any castaway. Rob and Aura were able to add a few items to the tally as well. Sadly, this effort was not enough to overcome the early deficit, and Hokkigai faced the first tribal council of the season. On a more positive note, there was a clear consensus among the tribe with regard to the direction of the vote. Leroy had been completely inactive since the marooning, failing to contribute to the challenge or discuss the impending vote, resulting in his unanimous elimination. Due to the straightforward nature of this cycle, no official alliances were formed, although the social center of the tribe appears to be the pair of Dicy and Slaytan. Dicy nets the only CP rating of the tribe for his early positioning as well as the strong game aptitude displayed in his confessionals. MORs and UTRs abound for the remaining members of the tribe, with the exception of Leroy, whose INV status led to his permanent disappearance from the game in the form of a torch snuff. CONTENDERS: The episode one contenders were incredibly tricky to narrow down - This cast has been amazing so far, and there are so many stand out competitors! Treb is topping us up though, with a great opening to the season!! As mentioned before, he has a very good set up on Ebi. He’s very talkative, which was received well by all of his tribemates, and he put lots of effort into the challenge and game talk! That trio alliance, his connection with Mana, and his high social ability will all contribute to his future success. Following right behind him is PBJ. Unagi is looking great right now, and PBJ certainly seems to have what it takes to make that work in her favor. Contributing lots to challenges, immediately setting up a power trio, using her weaknesses to her advantage - it makes her very strong, and gives her a great game sense. She’s easily the best person to align yourself with on that tribe. Next up is Dicy! He was the the most active member of Hokkigai by far, and knows that he can easily sail out of this tribe into swap - And knows what he can do to make that happen. The musings in his confessional show the strength of his game sense, and his ability to position himself in a way that nearly guarantees his success in the coming rounds… On this tribe, or on the next. Jenna is rounding out our list - Which makes these contenders have one member of every tribe! How fun!! Sake had less going on this cycle, but Jenna proved herself with activity levels and strategic thinking in her confessionals, as well as creating a solid connection with Pickles that was returned wholeheartedly!

Episode Two: “Unfortunate, but what can you do amiright?” - Winley Sake: Sake tribe started off the episode riding high after avoiding tribal the previous round. As a result of their previous victory, Kyran was sent to The Tank by Hokkigai, becoming the first castaway to take a dip into this watery unknown along with PBJ. After spending the entirety of the first night in the holding area, Kyran ultimately elected to explore the more difficult-to-navigate Fishing Dock, but he and PBJ were unable to uncover the extent of its mysteries. Meanwhile, the Coupnament challenge was underway, which saw Winley be the only member from Sake to advance to the final round, where they placed fourth. Facing tribal council for the first time, the social dynamics of Sake were less defined compared to other tribes, as they were lacking in both a strong core alliance and an inactive member to serve as an easy boot. However, within an hour after the challenge, chaos began to ensue with Winley at the center of it. First, they revealed to Jenna their intent to send Etay to The Tank in order to keep him alive long enough to connect with at a swap. Then, they went to Pickles with an elaborate plan to eliminate Kyran while throwing their own vote on Jenna in case of an idol play. Alarmed by this erratic playstyle and not wanting to risk losing Jenna, Pickles confided in her with Winley's plans, and the two were able to able to pull in Kyran and Zacharie to send Winley home 4-1. Winley received an OTTN rating due to their scheming being met with confusion and dismay by the rest of the tribe. Jenna and Pickles earn CPs for formulating the vote and further cementing their social and strategic connection with each other, while Zacharie and Kyran were less strategically instrumental, and get MORs. Hokkigai: Camp was quiet but friendly at the Hokkigai tribe, where Rob was able to secure immunity for the tribe and a day off from the tribe. Having set up no alliances after the first vote, the tribe is unified but lacks a clear voting bloc. Rob enjoyed being celebrated by the tribe for carrying them to the win in the coup-nament, earning him an OTTP rating. Dicy and Aura connected a bit in 1on1s, although they failed to build trust or set up an alliance, netting them MORs. Dicy put a little more social game into his confessionals, where he made a Hokkigai modpack in Minecraft for trust rankings. Slaytan took a backseat in the tribe compared to the last cycle, feeling confident in taking the day off after the challenge win, and secured a UTR rating. Unagi: The Apes alliance of Annie, Etay, & PBJ continues to be the focal point of the tribe. PBJ was chosen to go to The Tank for this episode alongside Kyran from Sake, but was unable to make any real progress on the challenge held within the "hard" path they chose. While she was away, things were mostly quiet on the tribe, but Etay had some endearing vulnerability about mental health and his struggles within his confessional. PBJ & Etay both found it prudent to try and further their relationship with Fones for future maneuverability, but Stephen still finds himself on the outside looking in when it comes to survivability if they were to go to tribal. Fortunately for everyone on Unagi, Annie & Etay took first and second place respectively in the immunity challenge, making them the only tribe with a fully in-tact 5 members. PBJ's erratic trip to the tank earned her an OTT, while Etay got a complex-positive rating for his confessionals.

Ebi: Although they put in a lot of effort practicing, the Ebi tribe failed to make an appearance in the finals of the coup-nament and were once again finding themselves at tribal council. The main alliance Slay-Ebiday consisting of Mana, Treb and Sky sought to target the remaining player on the outs, Noah. Although Noah tried a little to get some votes onto Mana, it was quickly apparent that he wasn't going to be successful. His tribemates did however really enjoy Noah and had only positive things to say about him, and while they were regretful for having to do so, they sent Noah home in a 3-1 vote. Mana, Treb and Noah all get P tones this episode, Mana and Treb for their effort in the challenge, conversations and perceptions regarding their tribemates and Noah for the positive feelings his tribe had for him and their sadness in having to send him home. Mana and Treb also get CPs for their strategic thoughts and for all but solidifying themselves as a F2 pair, planning on voting out Sky if they had to go to tribal again. CONTENDERS: This episode we see a little bit of a change! Treb stays right at the top, his positioning on the tribe (both with the three person alliance, and his incredibly close duo with Mana) is great and he has lots of tools for success heading into the future. The biggest thing that sets Treb and Mana apart right now is the worry about Mana’s newbie mindset causing them to make some beginner’s mistakes that could cost her the game. But she’s hot on the heels of contenders, that’s for sure! Jenna rises up in the rankings. Being able to solidify strong enough bonds with her tribe to sus out some early instances of word twisting benefitted her greatly - And it sets her up wonderfully, having a (now solidified) duo with Pickles. Her confessionals also prove her game awareness and forward thinking! PBJ takes on third place! They had multiple alliances set up, and some great game sense - They’re really good at getting a good read on things and even when it turns into paranoia, she can lean into it and make it work for her - Unlike Etay, who might let it take him over. She’s in the best spot on her tribe and was playing super cleanly, while also understanding that she could willingly dump their tribe come swap. Annie similarly, is playing very well - Will not get targeted before the rest of his tribe and could very well sail to merge, he’s done a great job setting up roots here. Only time will tell if they hold up!

Sake: Sake tribe had another interesting episode with a lot of moving parts. While they were not alone in failing to solve the cipher challenge, their standing in the tiebreaker was not enough to keep them safe from tribal council, which they would have to face for the second time in a row. The Winley boot in the previous episode came and went without seeing any alliance channels formed, so the social dynamics of Sake appeared once more to be in a more fluid state. In the immediate aftermath of the challenge attempt, Kyran and Zacharie remained in VC and solidified their intentions to work together. Their target for the vote was Pickles, but given the close connection between Pickles and Jenna, this would soon be put to the test. With the numbers being so small, Jenna was approached with the idea of voting out Pickles in order to avoid rocks, but she did not view this move as being in her best interest, and informed Pickles that their name was out. Faced with this information, Pickles began to work overtime to shift the target, feeling out both Kyran and Zacharie too see if one would flip on the other. Without much pressure at all, Kyran went to Jenna and expressed a willingness to vote out Zacharie, an opening that was quickly seized upon. Zacharie ultimately ended up flipping as well, and voting Kyran, and the other two, now in a swing position, mused about who was the better target, but there was ultimately not enough time to solidify a Kyran vote, and Zacharie was eliminated in 16th place. This cycle saw every member of Sake tribe earn a CP rating, as everyone played a crucial role in this vote with the numbers being so small. Jenna got the highest visibility for being the most central figure in determining the outcome, while Kyran and Zacharie also received a mixed tone for being perceived as less reliable allies moving forward. (edited)

Hokkigai: The Hokkigai tribe has been a notably quieter and slower tribe compared to the others and as a result not much of note happened for them this episode. They were seemingly going to flop in the challenge which would have shaken some things up, but narrowly secured victory in the final moments thanks to Rob (earning him an OTTP rating once again). Aura did get to visit The Tank, earning her a CP for her work on that and cross tribe discussion, but ultimately she was unable to walk away with any advantages. This leaves Dicy and Slaytan, who both get a MOR for mostly just vibing throughout the episode. In Hokkigai’s defense, there wasn’t much that needed to happen, so the relaxed attitude and gameplay is very reasonable. (edited)

This became even more important when it was clear they were not going to win the challenge. A good majority of this episode for Ebi was struggling with the challenge and the impending doom of a 3-person tribal council. That is what earns Mana and Treb their OTT ratings, as the actual discussion for tribal was minimal, they were all in on the challenge. Sky gets a MOR for being less involved in the challenge and generally not very present for the tribal. But they pushed through and all accepted it was do or die time. While they ultimately did not do it, the tribe kept their heads held high and set their sights on what was to come. (edited)

Unagi: With yet another great challenge performance the Unagi tribe was once again able to avoid tribal. Even though they didn't have to worry about tribal, there was still some decent development for the tribe. CONTENDERS: Jenna rises up to the #1 contender spot this episode as it is possible for Treb to get swap-screwed or targeted as a solo player in the upcoming swap. Jenna’s strong gameplay on the Sake tribe helped save their number one ally Pickles from elimination, and they continue to have good reads and gamesense without forming a target on her back. Treb falls to the second spot since he may have a tricky swap ahead of him, but he is a strong enough player to still be considered for contenders even with that in mind. It’s very likely that Pickles and Jenna will be a strong duo that could go very far in this game. Dicy rejoins contenders in our 4th position as he has made the most out of a tribe that didn’t have much to give socially or strategically. Like the other contenders, his game sense has been very strong and he is well positioned going into the merge, but his allies are night as tight or reliable as the other contenders, and his threat level is already starting to show itself which may become a problem down the road.

Uramaki: The Uramaki tribe had a relatively quiet start coming into the swap as most of the tribe members felt fairly comfortable with their groupings. From Hokkigai there was the trio of Dicy, Aura and Slaytan while from Unagi there was Etay, Fones and Stephen. That left Mana as the sole Ebi tribe member and only solo on the tribe. A bit unexpectedly, neither group sought out to scoop up Mana for a majority, but rather looked to form bonds with the opposing larger group in hopes to make some strong alliances come the merge. The two key players at the top of the tribe are Dicy and Etay who quickly bonded and formed the Cuties Please alliance consisting of Dicy, Etay, Fones and Slaytan. Coming into the challenge the pairings of Aura, Slaytan and Mana worked together to diffuse the first bomb, while Dicy and Etay worked to diffuse the second. Things were looking a little dicy for both groups in the challenge, however they both managed to diffuse the bombs, securing immunity for the cycle. Dicy and Etay earn CPs for being the key players in the formation of the Cuties Please alliance and for taking control of the tribe in a quiet but efficient manner. Mana, Aura and Slaytan get MORs for taking part in some good conversation and building trust with their tribemates, but otherwise stuck to the status quo. Stephen and Fones were relatively UTR this cycle outside of some initial odd comments by Stephen at the start of the cycle, but most people either ignored or brushed off the things he was saying. (edited)
11:57 PM
Maki: The warm atmosphere at Maki’s first meeting is partially the result of a healthy mix of new faces from different tribes. The largest group that arrived together were the final three members of Sake, Jenna, Pickles, and Kyran. The only pair were Annie and PBJ from Unagi, with the remaining Treb from Ebi and Rob from Hokkigai arriving alone. Despite Annie and Jenna making quick work of the first bomb, disarming it faster than anyone in the challenge, Treb and Pbj exploded sending Maki to the first tribal council of the swap. Battle lines were quickly drawn up after the challenge, with Treb, Annie, Rob, and PBJ forming the TARP alliance. With the safety of numbers, Annie suggested a move on Kyran as the weak link among the Sake group and Treb set out to make the pitch to Jenna and Pickles. To make that happen, Treb, Jenna, and Pickles set up the Arsonists Anonymous alliance, making Kyran the only tribe member not in any alliance chat at the first vote and the first member of Maki to be voted out. Annie and Treb earn CPs this episode for taking control and operating effectively to pull off a unanimous first vote on the new swap tribe; Jenna earns her CP this episode for her careful management of any issues with the plan at the vote by managing Rob’s concern at Kyran writing his name down. Rob, PBJ, and Pickles were happy to let a vote that they weren’t targeted at roll by quietly, netting them MOR ratings. Kyran meanwhile wasn’t able to navigate this cycle in terms of making connections, and takes home a MOR rating. (edited)
11:58 PM
CONTENDERS: Treb moves back up to the #1 spot as he was able to quickly but quietly form strong bonds with all of his tribemates and become a key player in the two main alliances on the Maki tribe. He was also able to push a Kyran vote which helped retain his positioning as a middle player without alarming or upsetting either group. Playing the middle can be a dangerous game but Treb is doing a great job doing so without making any waves thus far. Jenna falls to the #2 contenders spot this episode solely as a result of Treb moving up.
